selector.exact:
Western blot analysis of cell lysates and culture media of HeLa cells transiently
transfected with HA-tagged COCH under reducing gel electrophoresis
conditions. Intracellularly, all cochlins (both wild-type and all mutants) were produced,
but different band intensities of cochlins with various mutations were detected, in
relation to β-actin internal control. This indicates successful transfection and
expression of all cochlins, but different levels of intracellular cochlins. However, in
culture media of transfected cells, cochlin bands were detected only for wild-type and
three mutants, but not the other five mutants, indicating lack of secretion of these
cochlins. Untransfected HeLa cells and HeLa cells transfected with the pcDNA3 empty vector
(mock) were used as negative controls.

selector.exact:
Western blot analysis of cell lysates and culture media from HeLa cells transiently
transfected with HA-tagged COCH under non-reducing gel electrophoresis
conditions. Additional dimeric cochlin bands were observed for p.V104del, p.I109T, and
p.F121S. High-molecular-weight aggregates were detected for p.C162Y and p.A487P mutant
cochlins. No aggregates were detected in culture media, and five out of eight mutant
cochlins tested were not secreted. The five mutants that failed to be secreted were the
same ones that showed dimer and aggregate formation in cell lysates.

electrophoresis conditions, with and without PNGase F digestion (–, PNGase F
untreated; +, PNGase F treated). The predicted additional N-linked glycosylation site in
the p.109T mutant cochlin was confirmed with the observation of a larger band shift of the
mutant vs. wild-type cochlin after digestion.

rows.text:
For functional pathway, consider grouping all the ontology IDs in one line item, then the human readable forms in a second line. Note in protocol to annotate in the same order, that way the user knows the first ID correlates with the first nomenclature listed below.

Just an interesting note under molecular etiology. If a paper is insisting both gain of function and loss of function, is this more indicative of not knowing the appropriate assay involved in disease. YO=ou all may want to consider how you want to give guidance to this. I would not normally expect to see both LOF anf GOF of a protein for one disease, not to say it could not have these, but it would be good to be clear for your report is it over the  individual variants , or the experiment as a whole.

Again concerning the variants section, for the end user, it might be nice to separate each variant by an individual line.  You may want to consider also segregating based on those variants that are considered or asserted as pathogenic, benign, or unknown.

So I am realizing something form the variant results annotations. 

We may want to talk and reconsider the "Variant;" tag, and if it is really helping us serve a purpose beyond the CAID or variant ID. In this case the example is Variant:6. I can see how this could get time intensive and mistakes may get made. 

In the future if we have a structured app that can keep track of this data that would be good. If currently we ask people to keep track of this it certainly may seem onerous if there is not a really good reason for keeping it.
